paragraphs.bookText: Chapter 14: Once More into the Breach

Laran refused to leave until after midday. He had a date with Sionnach for lunch on the east bridge, also called Lord’s Grace Bridge, a nod to the wealthy neighborhood it connected to. The bridge had a magnificent view of the mountains east of the city, which they admired from the stone railing. Closer to the river’s inflow to the city, the river smelled like a river and not like a sewer, which it did from the western bridges.
“I don’t know anything about you,” he said. “Have you lived here long?”
“No. I’m new to the city.”
“What brought you here?”

“I lived with my brothers and sisters in the woods near a small village,” she said, looking out over the water. The god’s breath stirred her hair, swirling it across her face. “Or did until I lost my parents.”
The blood drained from his face. “I’m… I’m so sorry. I shouldn’t have asked.”
“It’s okay,” she said, putting a hand on his arm. “But without her, there wasn’t enough for everyone. So I came here, to Raffica.”

Her leaving meant one less mouth to feed. The difference between life and death for a poor peasant family. He almost offered to give her money but stopped. It might feel like he was trying to buy her affection. He’d find some other way to help her. Except he had to leave in a few hours.
“I’m leaving again, but only for a few days,” he told her.
“Is it dangerous?”
“Unfortunately.”
After an uncomfortable silence, she pulled out a nosegay from her pocket. “Take this to remember me by. If I’d known, I’d have made something better.”
He accepted the cloth packet of herbs and flowers. Impulsively, he tried to kiss her, but she backed away. “Not here,” she said, blushing.

It broke the moment, and they spent the rest of the lunch awkwardly avoiding talking about his trip. Eventually, he walked her back to the Old Glory, where she left him. Feeling like a jerk, he made his way back to the house he shared with Daisy.
“Think this thing will hold us?” Daisy asked Laran as the priests of the Sleeping Gods lowered the cage into the pit.
“It has before.”

He did wonder, though. The winch didn’t look like it held enough chain to go more than three hundred yards or so. How did they get delvers down to the lower levels? He’d worry about that when the time came. Somehow, he felt certain this wouldn’t be his last trip down into this hole.

The smooth rock sides of the fifty-foot-wide pit went by slowly. The heavy chain holding them clanked and rattled ominously as the cage swayed over the seemingly bottomless hole. Laran figured they were three hundred yards down before it came to a jerky halt, fifteen feet short of the ragged hole in the wall.
[Favor for a Frenemy]
[Objective completed: Descend to the third level of the Pit of the Sleeping God]
[Objective: Locate the Band of Severing]
“Hey!” Daisy shouted up to the priests. “A little more.”
“I don’t think they can hear you.”
“Or they don’t want to.”
“You were rude about being searched.”
“Nobody touches me there without my permission. He’s lucky he still has all his fingers.”
“Lead underwear?” Laran said. “You were trying to cheat their system.”

As usual, the priests weighed and searched them before letting them into the pit. They charged by the weight of loot recovered, and delvers always tried to weigh themselves down with things they could leave behind and replace with treasure.
“Cheat is such an ugly word.”
“Looks like they aren’t going to lower it any further. Time to climb.”
“I don’t climb,” she said, looking down into the darkness nervously.
“Just lower yourself on the rope. I’ll haul you in.”
“Promise you’ll catch me?”

He looked at the seven-foot-tall tauran, with her tree trunk thighs, barrel chest, and bodybuilder arms as big as his legs. She probably weighed twice what he did, and without an ounce of fat. Three times in her armor.
“Are you going to take off the plate mail?”
“Do I have to?”
“No, but it would help.”

With an overly dramatic sigh, she began to strip. He hastily lowered himself out of the cage until he got even with the entrance hole. Kipping his body to swing toward the opening, he got close enough to grab the lower lip. He hauled himself in, pulling the end of the rope behind him.

Looking up, he saw Daisy lowering her armor in the Pack of Half Measures. Once he pulled it in, she began her descent, grumbling the whole way. Fortunately, they’d let her keep the cotton padding underneath the lead undergarments. He made sure not to let his eyes roam where they weren’t wanted.
“You don’t need to look away,” she said, her hooves finally on solid ground.
“I didn’t want to make it awkward.”
“You can be such a prude.”

The hole in the pit’s side was part of a ten-foot-long, crudely worked tunnel that broke into a building on the far side. Compared to everything else they’d seen in the pit, it looked like recent work. Laran guessed that without any obvious entrance at this depth, someone tunneled through the pit wall to create one.

On the first two levels, the priests left scales for prospective delvers to weigh their loot prior to ascending. No such courtesy here. Not even a pull rope to signal when they wanted to be pulled out. To be fair, pull ropes to ring a bell didn’t work very well at three hundred yards. Instead, the priests would lower the cage at sunrise and sunset for one week. After that, they assumed the delvers had succumbed to the dangers of the pit.

Beyond the short tunnel, they entered the back of a building made of long, flat shale stones chinked with dried mud. The builders made no attempt to smooth the walls, even going so far as to use larger slabs to form natural shelves. Whatever served as doors or windows had decayed to dust centuries ago. It had a distinctly more primitive look than the earlier levels.

Laran’s miner’s band with a fresh moonstone mounted into it revealed the remains of large, rounded beams that formed a ceiling, but now lay crumbled and decayed on the floor. Through the open roof, they could see a relatively smooth stone cavern ceiling, just like on the other levels. Only this one sat some thirty feet overhead.

Stepping through the doorway, they found themselves in a small city square, just large enough for one building to face it on each side. Beyond that was a twisting maze of narrow streets. All the buildings they could see had similar construction to the one they left. Though the immediate area felt lifeless and still, they could hear stones clattering and an occasional clang in the distance. The open space below the high stone ceiling created an echo chamber, making it impossible to determine the direction, or even distance, of the noises.
“Which way does that gemstone say to go?” Daisy asked as Laran chalked the doorway to their exit.
“It’s not like a compass. It gets brighter the closer we get. We don’t know if we’re heading in the right direction until we travel a while.”
“So which way?”
“Patch said north by northwest.”
“And which way is that?”
Laran pointed. Unfortunately, he pointed back toward the pit. The temple lay on the southern side of the pit, which meant they had to circle around it first.

Shaking her head in disgust, Daisy extended her hand, indicating he should lead the way. The alleys bent at arbitrary angles, making the buildings anything but square. Every now and then, they’d encounter another small open neighborhood square.

They needed to keep the pit close until they got to the far side of it, so at every junction, they turned right. This meant ending up at a lot of dead-ends. Laran chalked the intersections so they could find their way back.

As they walked, they heard harsh sounds that grew louder and louder. The stone ceiling rose to fifty feet or more, and they walked through more and more two and three-story buildings. Laran decided to climb one to see if he could get a fix on the sounds. He shut down his light, not wanting to attract attention. By common agreement, he and Daisy used hand signals whenever possible to avoid making unnecessary sounds.

Perched on the top of the crumbling wall, the inky black resisted his Shadevision perk. He thought about getting another rank or two of that perk when he leveled up, but doubted he’d be able to pass up other options. He cast ICU, even though he knew it had a uselessly short range for this situation. Predictably, he saw no electrical fields from living creatures within twenty-five feet other than Daisy. Of course, being over twenty feet off the ground, that didn’t mean squat.
“There are sounds all around us,” Laran whispered to Daisy when he got back down. “As far as I can tell, the big sounds are ahead. The echoes in this place make it hard to get a good fix.”
“Guess we just keep going and hope for the best.”
“That’s a terrible strategy, but I don’t see an alternative.”

They had no choice but to use the moonstone. Without it, they couldn’t see their hands in front of their faces. Laran hoped that anything predatory that lived down here was blind, like most cave species. He pinged ICU every few seconds, waiting just long enough to recover the Anima it took. If anything tried to ambush them, he should spot it in advance.

Daisy pantomimed fighting and touched her ear. It sounded like combat to him too, but without the shouts and grunts people would produce. A large structure loomed ahead, in far better shape than the surrounding ruins.

Stepping around a corner, an alien battlefield greeted them. The four-story, terraced building made of large, quarried stones stood in stark contrast to the other buildings. A horde of giant insects occupied the structure, crowding the terraces, and gathered in a defensive formation in front of it. Facing them was an army of slugs, snails, and tentacled things.

A fierce melee filled the large, open plaza. Man-sized black ants standing on their back four legs, like the centaur scrofa, wielded chitin shields and jagged blades. Smaller red ants directed waist-high beetles with cruel-looking pincers on short leashes. Centisoldiers, familiar to him from an earlier foray into the pit, darted between them. Towering praying mantises waited on the lowest terrace.

Opposing them, giant snails, twice his height, oozed forward, heads withdrawn into their shells. Tentacled monstrosities bigger than Daisy lashed out at the ants, snatching and hurling them. Most had four tentacle arms, two of which wielded strange looking weapons. Four matching tentacles served as legs, pulling them across the rough ground. Chitin armor plated their faces, leaving four holes open for sensory stalks.

The boneless monstrosities pressed the insects hard. Though the slugs and squids looked grossly outnumbered, the bugs were far more fragile and died in droves. The combatants trampled the dead that lay everywhere. He saw tentacles severed from split open bulbous bodies, insect parts scattered like autumn leaves. Blue blood stained the ground below the octopoid corpses, while the insects shed a yellowish-green ichor.

In the center of the attacking forces, a worm ten feet in diameter and long enough its tail had yet to make it to the plaza, humped toward the building. It became immediately clear that the slime army sought to protect the worm long enough for it to get to the temple, while the bugs fought to get to it. Neither army seemed to care about the two spectators right now.

As they watch, fat star shaped oozes dropped from the ceiling into the middle of the insect army, smothering whatever they landed on. The praying mantises leaped into the fray, serrated arms reinforced with a metal coating. Slicing into the gooey starfish, they freed their compatriots.

Blobs of slime arced over the battle, landing among the bugs. Everything they touched hissed and steamed as if dipped in acid. Flying beetles launched from the highest terrace, dropping white powder on their slimy enemies. It dissolved the slugs on contact and forced the snails to maneuver around the piles.
“Holy shit,” Daisy whispered.
“You said it,” Laran said. “We need to go around all of this.”
“Oh, hell yes.”
[Battle Tactics +1]
[Monstrology +2]
[Monstrology 24: Choose new perk]

Apparently, he could learn something just by watching a battle between bugs and slimy things. Although with that skill being so low, it probably didn’t take much. With all the new creatures present, he wasn’t surprised he’d earned multiple Monstrology points. He’d pick his perks later, when he wasn’t in danger of being drawn into a fight.

Skirting the battle as best they could turned out not to be enough. A flash of Laran’s ICU revealed a half-dozen chest-high octopoid creatures ahead of them. The only egress from the street led to the plaza, but they ducked into it anyway. Laran cast Shhh on Daisy to help keep them undetected. The creatures oozed down the narrow street, probably trying to surprise the bugs with a flanking maneuver.

They moved surprisingly fast on four tentacles and pulled themselves forward, dragging their bellies over the worn cobblestone, leaving a trail of slime behind them. Two ten-foot-long tentacles held jagged-looking axes, and two remained unencumbered to do whatever. Unfortunately, the side alley Laran and Daisy retreated into was also the path the slime squad wanted.

The four armored eyestalks didn’t have eyeballs on them, but somehow they detected them anyway. Maybe it used something like Laran’s ICU spell or sensed their body heat. They marched two by two, which crowded the narrow street. Spotting the two intruders, the lead two surged forward, unfurling their long tentacles. His perks told him they had no special defenses, but did have some sort of damaging spit or spray.

Laran cast Have a Ball, throwing the sphere of lightning into their midst. Jagged white bolts of electricity enveloped all six of the octopoid creatures. The smell of their burning flesh filled the alley. Red Health bars over each showed they lost about 15 percent of their Health.
[Level 18 Terraken Skirmisher partially resisted Have a Ball II stun]
[Level 18 Terraken Skirmisher partially resisted Have a Ball II stun]
All six partially resisted his spell’s stun. He’d never seen anything partially resist an effect before. The result seemed to be that some limbs still worked, while others didn’t.

Daisy charged, intent on getting close enough to wield her weapon and negate their reach advantage. In these close quarters, she could only use one of her two-handed weapons and chose Betsy. Two chitin blades scythed at her, one from each terraken. She blocked one with the haft of her maul and let the other scrape across her plate mail. A pair of tentacles from the right-hand creature coiled around her weapon, futilely trying to rip it from her grasp.

Now inside their reach, Daisy swung Betsy like a baseball bat at one of the lead terrakens. The head of the giant maul burst into flames before shattering the chitin armor covering the creature’s body and squishing it into its neighbor. It looked like hitting jello as the two creatures compressed against the opposite wall.

Laran had no place to stand next to his friend without hindering her and risking a maul upside his head. However, he saw the rearmost pair pull themselves up onto the walls, slowed by paralyzed limbs. He whipped out the Crooked Bow and fired an arrow charged with Static Buildup at one of them and a fire arrow at the other.
[Level 18 Terraken Skirmisher partially resisted Static Buildup II stun]

The terraken hit by Betsy lost 20 percent of its Health, but the other only ten. The lead pair of octopoids oozed around Daisy, either to get to Laran or flank her. The two behind them flung themselves at the tauran. One had two functional limbs, the other three. Five simultaneous attacks were too much for Daisy to avoid, and a serrated blade scored a minor wound on her arm, sliding between the armor plates. One of the free tentacles wrapped itself around her ankle and yanked. Daisy didn’t budge, but the terraken pulled itself to her leg.

Laran pulled out Dead Man’s Gladius and Talon while casting Dark Armor. One of the two creatures Daisy smashed with Betsy lashed out at him with all four limbs, having recovered from the lightning stun. The other flailed at the tauran from beside her. He blocked two weapon attacks and severed a tentacle attempting to wrap up his arm. In close now, he stabbed with both weapons, adding Gloom Venom. Normally he’d add Hand Zap, but these creatures didn’t react as he’d expected to the lightning.

He lost track of Daisy when the wall-crawling octopoid on the other side lashed at his back with all four tentacles. Two blades cut into his legs, a tentacle wrapped around his neck, and another around his sword arm. He felt, rather than saw, Daisy breathe fire on her opponents.

Laran cast Currently Touching, zapping the tentacles looped around him. They held on, suffering the electrical charge. The one in front of him spit black ink in his face. It not only blinded, but burned him too.

Casting ICU showed him the blueish white nervous systems of the terrakens, but nothing else. They swam in total darkness, as if floating in outer space. Their brains stood out—a mass of electrical energy comparable to a person’s. There seemed to be a knot of nerves at the base of each tentacle.
[Intuition check with Monstrology bonus passed]
Holy shit! They had a miniature brain for each limb. That explained the partial resistance to his Lightning Magic. Each tentacle’s brain must be resisting the stun effect independently.

The tentacle choking him out forced him to set aside the biology lesson. Gritting his teeth, he let the beast in front of him slash open wounds on his legs. Instead, he stabbed the tentacle restraining his sword arm with Talon, adding Gloom Venom to it. It loosened but held tight until he cast What’s That on the tentacle’s brain. Then the octopoid released its grip. The tentacle around his neck seemed intent on popping his head like a zit. It didn’t have suckers, like an octopus, but hundreds of small boney hooks ideal for clinging to rough surfaces. And perfect for stripping the flesh from his neck. A backward slice of Dead Man’s Gladius, also with Gloom Venom, cut the tentacle in two.

ICU drained his Anima too quickly for this fight to go on for long. He had maybe twenty to thirty seconds before he’d run out. Laran drove his short sword deep into the soft body of the terraken, coming at it from the side to avoid the face armor. Seeing the thing’s brain proved useful when his blade ran it through.

The creature spasmed, limbs flailing in its death throes. Its electrical pathways dimmed as he turned to attack the one behind him. It tried to stay at a distance where its reach had the advantage, but he leaped high and landed hard on the carapace armor. Feeling for the edge with his hand, he repeated his earlier maneuver, stabbing directly into its brain.

Anima depleted, he felt his way to the wall and put his back to it. Swinging Dead Man’s Gladius in front of him, he hoped his eyesight would return soon. Shortly after the sounds of combat ceased, a huge hand intercepted his forearm mid-swing.
“They’re all dead,” Daisy said, leaning against the wall next to him. “Those damn things kept sliding their tentacles under my armor.”
